Lesser stick-nest rat

Leporillus apicalis

Blamed on cats

IUCN status: Extinct

Last seen: Leporillus apicalis were last seen in 1933 in Norman Tindale, near Mt Crombie, south of the Musgrave Ranges in north-western South Australia (IUCN 2023)

IUCN claim: “The arrival of Red Foxes in range may have driven remnant subpopulations to extinction”

Studies in support

Lesser stick-nest rats were last confirmed in the NT, NSW, Victoria and SA 7-48 years after cats arrived (Current submission).

Studies not in support

No studies

Is the threat claim evidence-based?

There are no studies evidencing a link between cats and the extinction of lesser stick-nest rats.

Evidence linking Leporillus apicalis to cats. Last records of extirpated populations relative to earliest local records of cats. Error bars show record uncertainty range. Predator arrival records were digitized from Abbott 2008. Small points show unconfirmed records (excluded from analyses).

References

Abbott, The spread of the cat, Felis catus, in Australia: re-examination of the current conceptual model with additional information. Conservation Science Western Australia 7 (2008).

Current submission (2023) Scant evidence that introduced predators cause extinctions.

IUCN Red List. https://www.iucnredlist.org/ Accessed June 2023
